13px;\n    color: #777;\n    margin-top: 12px;\n  }\n  .cta-trust span {\n    margin: 0 8px;\n  }\n  .faq-item {\n    border-bottom: 1px solid #e0e0e0;\n    padding: 18px 0;\n  }\n  .faq-item summary {\n    font-weight: 700;\n    font-size: 16px;\n    cursor: pointer;\n    list-style: none;\n    display: flex;\n    justify-content: space-between;\n    align-items: center;\n  }\n  .faq-item summary::after {\n    content: \"⌄\";\n    font-size: 20px;\n    color: #999;\n  }\n  .faq-item p, .faq-item ul {\n    margin-top: 12px;\n    font-size: 15px;\n    color: #444;\n    line-height: 1.7;\n  }\n  .faq-item ul {\n    padding-left: 20px;\n  }\n  .timeline-grid {\n    display: grid;\n    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;\n    gap: 16px;\n    margin: 24px 0;\n  }\n  .timeline-item {\n    background: #f9f9f9;\n    border-radius: 8px;\n    padding: 16px 18px;\n  }\n  .timeline-item .timeline-label {\n    font-weight: 700;\n    font-size: 13px;\n    color: #c9a96e;\n    text-transform: uppercase;\n    letter-spacing: 1px;\n    margin-bottom: 8px;\n  }\n  .timeline-item p {\n    font-size: 14px;\n    margin: 0;\n    color: #444;\n  }\n  img.full-width {\n    width: 100%;\n    border-radius: 10px;\n    margin: 20px 0;\n  }\n  .section-divider {\n    border: none;\n    border-top: 1px solid #e8e8e8;\n    margin: 48px 0;\n  }\n  @media (max-width: 600px) {\n    h1.headline { font-size: 26px; }\n    h2 { font-size: 21px; }\n    .timeline-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }\n  }\n</style>\n\n<div class=\"announcement-top\">\n  Over 120,000 purchased last month — Limited availability\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"page-content\">\n\n  <h1 class=\"headline\">Hormonal facial hair: why it keeps getting worse no matter what you try — and what to do instead</h1>\n\n  <p class=\"intro-subtitle\">I've seen hundreds of women with hormonal hair resistant to everything.<br>\n  The real cause of the worsening isn't what they think.<br>\n  And the hair removal industry has every incentive not to tell you.</p>\n\n  <div class=\"author-block\">\n    Dr. Elena Rossi · Dermatologist · Specialist in Women's Hormonal Health<br>\n    Published May 19, 2026 · 9 min read\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"section-divider\">\n\n  <p>She wakes up at 5:30. She locks the bathroom door.<br>\n  She pulls the tweezers from the same drawer as always.</p>\n\n  <p>Forty-five minutes in front of the magnifying mirror. One by one.<br>\n  She already knows she'll be late for work.<br>\n  She already knows that by noon she'll have to start all over again.</p>\n\n  <p>She's already tried waxing. The razor. Threading.<br>\n  Laser — €4,200, twelve sessions, results worsened.</p>\n\n  <p>She's already heard three doctors tell her: <em>\"It's hormonal. Manage it.\"</em></p>\n\n  <p>What no one has ever explained to her is why it keeps getting worse.<br>\n  And that there is a way to break the cycle.</p>\n\n  <p>Every day women come to my practice with this story.<br>\n  Years of attempts. Methods changed. Money spent.</p>\n\n  <p>And one constant that never changes: facial hair has become thicker, darker, faster to grow back.</p>\n\n  <p>Anxiety higher. Daily routine longer and longer.</p>\n\n  <p>The question they always ask is the same: <em>\"What am I doing wrong?\"</em></p>\n\n  <p>The answer they don't expect is this: they are using the wrong removal method.</p>\n\n  <p>Not the product. Not the frequency. <strong>The method itself</strong> — whatever it is — is making the situation worse every single day.</p>\n\n  <p>Here's why.</p>\n\n  <hr class=\"section-divider\">\n\n  <div class=\"step-number\">1</div>\n\n  <h2>Tweezers, wax, and threading: every pull teaches the body to produce stronger hair</h2>\n\n  <img class=\"full-width\" src=\"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0921/5538/0039/files/713C0FFE-04FD-4FB6-BB51-6CEA4D611C42.png?v=1779298938\" alt=\"Dermelia treatment\">\n\n  <p>When you remove a hair by pulling it from the root — with tweezers, wax, or threading — the follicle undergoes a micro-trauma.</p>\n\n  <p>The body registers that action exactly as it would register a wound: an attack on an area to be protected. And it responds by reinforcing its defenses.</p>\n\n  <p>The follicle receives more blood, more nourishment. The next hair grows back thicker, darker, harder.</p>\n\n  <p>Not just because of hormones alone, but as a biological protective response. It's the same mechanism by which skin thickens where it's repeatedly injured in the same spot.</p>\n\n  <h3>The pull-trauma cycle — how it worsens over time</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"steps-grid\">\n    <div class=\"step-item\">\n      <div class=\"step-title\">Mechanical pulling</div>\n      <p>Tweezers, wax, threading: the hair is removed from the root. The follicle registers a wound.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"step-item\">\n      <div class=\"step-title\">Defensive response</div>\n      <p>The body sends more blood and nourishment to the follicle to protect the area. It perceives it as a zone under attack.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"step-item\">\n      <div class=\"step-title\">Stronger regrowth</div>\n      <p>The follicle produces a thicker, darker, more resistant hair to defend itself against the next pull.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"step-item\">\n      <div class=\"step-title\">The cycle worsens</div>\n      <p>Each pull makes the next one worse. Year after year, hair becomes increasingly difficult to manage and routines grow longer.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <p>A woman who had a few fine hairs at 25 has dozens of thick, coarse ones by 35 — even if she followed every piece of medical advice to the letter.</p>\n\n  <p>It's not her fault. It's not just the hormones' fault. <strong>It's the daily removal method that has amplified everything.</strong></p>\n\n  <div class=\"quote-block\">\n    \"The hormonal cause — polycystic ovary, menopause, postpartum fluctuations — starts the problem. But it's the removal method that amplifies it every morning, until it becomes unmanageable.\"\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"review-block\">\n    <div class=\"review-stars\">★★★★★</div>\n    <p>\"I woke up at 5:30 every morning to pull them out before anyone saw me. After ten years with tweezers, what had been a few fine hairs had become dozens of wires as hard as metal. I couldn't understand why it kept getting worse, even though I was doing everything they told me.\"</p>\n    <div class=\"review-author\">— Giulia M., 34 · polycystic ovary · verified buyer</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"section-divider\">\n\n  <div class=\"step-number\">2</div>\n\n  <h2>The razor seems gentler — but it still triggers a defensive follicle response</h2>\n\n  <img class=\"full-width\" src=\"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0921/5538/0039/files/811838B7-52A5-49D6-8F4D-0CF4DCA89AA6.png?v=1779298935\" alt=\"Razor on face\">\n\n  <p>The razor doesn't pull the hair from the root: it cuts it at skin level. That's why many women choose it thinking it's less traumatic than tweezers or wax.</p>\n\n  <p>In part that's true — it doesn't create the same pull micro-trauma.</p>\n\n  <p>But it creates a different problem, equally damaging over time.</p>\n\n  <p>Hair cut flush with the skin grows back with a blunt tip, without the natural point it had before. To the touch — and to the eye — it immediately seems thicker and darker, even if biologically it hasn't changed.</p>\n\n  <p>But the real problem is something else: frequent shaving stimulates the follicle to produce hair more continuously and rapidly, because the body perceives constant removal as a signal to keep production active.</p>\n\n  <p>Over time, women who use a razor on their face invariably report the same thing: regrowth becomes faster and more visible just hours after. The routine becomes more frequent. And leaving the house without having shaved becomes impossible.</p>\n\n  <div class=\"warning-box\">\n    <div class=\"warning-title\">⚠ RAZOR ON THE FACE — WHAT HAPPENS OVER TIME</div>\n    <p><strong>Regrowth with a blunt tip:</strong> hair appears immediately thicker and darker just hours later.</p>\n    <p><strong>Continuous follicle stimulation:</strong> frequent shaving keeps the follicle in constant production mode, accelerating growth cycles.</p>\n    <p><strong>Growing dependency:</strong> the more you shave, the more frequently you're forced to. The window of \"smooth skin\" shortens over time.</p>\n    <p style=\"color:#c0392b; font-weight:700; margin-top:14px;\">✗ It doesn't solve the problem — it accelerates it</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"section-divider\">\n\n  <div class=\"step-number\">3</div>\n\n  <h2>Laser on hormonal hair: why it often makes things worse instead of better</h2>\n\n  <img class=\"full-width\" src=\"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0921/5538/0039/files/14F1E2FF-A45F-4E77-A4D7-2AF205D6722F.png?v=1779298939\" alt=\"Laser hormonal hair\">\n\n  <p>Laser is the most recommended solution by doctors for hormonal facial hair. It's also the one that, in practice, disappoints most often — and in some cases significantly worsens the situation.</p>\n\n  <p>Laser works well on hair with stable roots, unaffected by continuous hormonal fluctuations. Hormonal hair is different: its growth is constantly stimulated by hormones, even during and after treatment.</p>\n\n  <p>Laser can destroy the existing hair, but it cannot block the hormonal signal that continues to stimulate new hairs.</p>\n\n  <p>The result that many women see after 8–12 sessions costing hundreds of euros each is always the same: the hair comes back.</p>\n\n  <p>In some cases — the so-called <strong>laser paradox effect</strong> — it comes back thicker than before, because the thermal trauma activated in the follicles the same defensive response that tweezers would have triggered. The body responded to the thermal aggression by reinforcing hair production.</p>\n\n  <p>After months of sessions, appointments, and money spent, many women find themselves exactly where they started: continuous regrowth, sensitized skin, and an even more invasive routine.</p>\n\n  <p>Not because laser \"never works,\" but because on hormonal hair <strong>it doesn't eliminate the cause that continues to feed it.</strong></p>\n\n  <div class=\"quote-block\">\n    \"This is not an isolated case. The laser paradox effect on hormonal hair is documented. The problem is that it is rarely communicated to patients — and almost never before starting treatment.\"\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"review-block\">\n    <div class=\"review-stars\">★★★★★</div>\n    <p>\"I spent €4,200 on laser. Twelve sessions. In the end the hairs had come back thicker than before. No one warned me that with polycystic ovary, laser could make things worse. I felt betrayed by all the doctors who had recommended it as a definitive solution.\"</p>\n    <div class=\"review-author\">— Rossana M., 38 · polycystic ovary · verified buyer</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <hr class=\"section-divider\">\n\n  <h2>The problem isn't just the hair. It's the way you remove it every day.</h2>\n\n  <p>The medical system tends to treat hormonal hair as an aesthetic problem to manage symptom by symptom — tweezers for the hairs, laser to reduce them, medication for the hormones.</p>\n\n  <p>But no one ever asks the question that would change everything: <strong>\"How do you remove them every day?\"</strong></p>\n\n  <p>Because it's from that answer that it depends whether the situation will improve or continue to get worse.</p>\n\n  <img class=\"full-width\" src=\"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0921/5538/0039/files/4F1F2011-D588-48CA-900C-7C8BAE81D72B.png?v=1779298937\" alt=\"Hair removal routine\">\n\n  <h3>It's time to change method.</h3>\n\n  <p>Stop stressing the follicle every day and switch to a routine designed to make regrowth visibly thinner, slower and more manageable over time.</p>\n\n  <a href=\"/products/kit-depilazione\" class=\"cta-btn\" style=\"display:inline-block; margin: 16px 0;\">Discover how →</a>\n\n  <hr class=\"section-divider\">\n\n  <h2>There is a method that removes without traumatizing — and follicles actually begin to heal</h2>\n\n  <p>The right question isn't \"which method works best to remove hair.\" The right question is: <strong>does a method exist that removes hair without activating the follicle's defensive response?</strong></p>\n\n  <p>Yes. And it works in a completely opposite way to everything you've tried so far.</p>\n\n  <p>It's called dissolution. Instead of pulling or cutting the hair — with the resulting trauma — dissolution gently dissolves the structure of the hair through the skin, with a formula based on natural ingredients.</p>\n\n  <p>The hair disintegrates beneath the surface without the follicle ever being touched. No wound. No danger signal. No defensive response.</p>\n\n  <p>The follicle receives no message to protect itself. It has no reason to strengthen itself.</p>\n\n  <p>And over time — without the continuous cycle of trauma and defense — hairs grow back progressively finer, not thicker.</p>\n\n  <img class=\"full-width\" src=\"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0921/5538/0039/files/5FB08AC4-4E64-48B7-B1EE-DF360C694B29.png?v=1779298938\" alt=\"Dermelia dissolution method\">\n\n  <h3>HOW DISSOLUTION WORKS — THE OPPOSITE MECHANISM TO PULLING</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"steps-grid\">\n    <div class=\"step-item\">\n      <div class=\"step-title\">Natural preparation</div>\n      <p>A formula based on botanical extracts softens and prepares the hair structure. Hormonal hairs are much more resistant than normal ones: this step is essential.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"step-item\">\n      <div class=\"step-title\">Gentle dissolution</div>\n      <p>The natural formula breaks down the hair beneath the skin's surface. No pulling. No contact with the follicle. No defensive body response.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"step-item\">\n      <div class=\"step-title\">Soothing treatment</div>\n      <p>A post-treatment formula with natural ingredients calms the skin and reduces any residual inflammation, helping follicles recover over time.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"step-item\">\n      <div class=\"step-title\">The cycle stops</div>\n      <p>Without repeated trauma, the follicle stops defending itself. Hairs grow back progressively finer. The situation improves instead of worsening.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <img class=\"full-width\" src=\"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0921/5538/0039/files/D3F95E2F-8AC2-4CDD-90DF-5481CCD91284.png?v=1779298928\" alt=\"Dermelia dissolution method\">\n\n  <h3>The pattern I observe in women who break the trauma cycle:</h3>\n\n  <img class=\"full-width\" src=\"https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0921/5538/0039/files/ACF55937-F44F-4D81-8EE6-1AED00647FD3.png?v=1779298936\" alt=\"Dermelia transformations\">\n\n  <div class=\"timeline-grid\">\n    <div class=\"timeline-item\">\n      <div class=\"timeline-label\">Days 3–5</div>\n      <p>Skin is soft immediately after treatment. No bristly effect, no visible irritation.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"timeline-item\">\n      <div class=\"timeline-label\">Weeks 2–3</div>\n      <p>Regrowth slows. Hairs that appear are visibly finer and lighter than before.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"timeline-item\">\n      <div class=\"timeline-label\">Month 2</div>\n      <p>Follicles begin to normalize. The defensive response gradually diminishes.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"timeline-item\">\n      <div class=\"timeline-label\">Month 3</div>\n      <p>The routine drops from 30–45 minutes a day to a few minutes a month. The relationship with the mirror changes.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <p>This method exists and it's called <strong>Dermelia Trilogy Kit:</strong> three complete phases, natural formula, developed specifically for thick and resistant hormonal hair.</p>\n\n  <hr class=\"section-divider\">\n\n  <h2>What women are saying</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"review-block\">\n    <div class=\"review-stars\">★★★★★</div